Let~$\EuScript{E}$ be a hypersurface in the space of infinite jets associated
to all prolongations of (\ref{main}). Recall that a \emph{conservation law}
of Equation (\ref{main}) is a differential form
\begin{equation*}
\fl
  \begin{array}{ll}
    \omega&=S\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz\wedge dt + T\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz\wedge ds +
    Z\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dt\wedge ds \\
    &+ Y\,dx\wedge dz\wedge dt\wedge ds +
    X\,dy\wedge dz\wedge dt\wedge ds
\end{array}
\end{equation*}
on~$\EuScript{E}$ such that
%\begin{equation*}\fl$$  d_h(\omega) \equiv
%\end{equation*}
%\begin{equation*}\fl
   \Big(D_s(S) - D_t(T) +D_z(Z) - D_y(Y) +
  D_x(X)\Big)\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz\wedge dt\wedge ds = 0,
%\end{equation*}
$$
where
%\begin{equation*}$ d_h=dx\wedge D_x+dy\wedge D_y + dz\wedge D_z + dt\wedge D_t + ds\wedge
 D_s$%\end{equation*}
   is the \emph{horizontal de~Rham differential}. A
conservation law is \emph{trivial} if~$\omega=d_h\theta$ for some
horizontal $3$-form~$\theta$.

Let~$\tilde{\omega}$ be an arbitrary extension of~$\omega$ from~$\EuScript{E}$
to the ambient jet space. Then
%\begin{equation*}$ d_h(\tilde{\omega})= \psi\cdot F\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz\wedge dt\wedge
 ds$%\end{equation*}
 for some function~$\psi$ on jets, where~$F=u_{yz}-u_{ts}-u_su_{xz}+u_zu_{xs}$.
The restriction~$\psi_\omega=\psi|_{\EuScript{E}}$ depends
on~$\omega$ only and is called the \emph{generating function}(or
the \emph{characteristic}) of the conservation law~$\omega$. The
following facts hold: a conservation law is trivial if and only if
its generating function
  vanishes;
generating functions enjoy the equation
  \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:2}
    D_xD_y(\psi) = D_tD_s(\psi) +2u_{xs}D_z(\psi) - 2u_{xz}D_s(\psi)
  \end{equation}
  formally adjoint to (\ref{eq:1}).
Solutions of Equation (\ref{eq:2}) are called \emph{cosymmetries}.
Solving Equation (\ref{eq:2}), we obtain the following set of
cosymmetries:
%\begin{equation*}%  \begin{array}{l}$$
    \psi_1=u_{xxx},\quad    \psi_2(V)=V,\quad \displaystyle
