Using the method described in \cite{Morozov2009,Morozov2014} we find a contact
integrable extension ({\sc cie}) for the structure equations of the symmetry
pseudo-group of Equation (\ref{main}). The {\sc cie} yields two coverings
of (\ref{main}). The first covering is defined by the system
\begin{equation}
\left\{
\begin{array}{lcl}
q_t &=& H\,q_z + u_z \, q_x,
\\
q_y &=& H\,q_s + u_s \, q_x,
\end{array}
\right.
\label{H_covering}
\end{equation}
where $H$ is a solution to
\begin{equation}
\left\{
\begin{array}{lcl}
H_t &=& H\,H_z,
\\
H_y &=& H\,H_s,
\\
H_x &=& 0.
\end{array}
\right.
\label{H_system}
\end{equation}
The second covering is defined by
\begin{equation}
\left\{
\begin{array}{lcl}
q_t &=& q\,q_z + u_z \, q_x,
\\
q_y &=& q\,q_s + u_s \, q_x.
\end{array}
\right.
\label{q_covering}
\end{equation}
System (\ref{H_system}) has constant solutions $H(t,y,z,s) \equiv \lambda =
\mathrm{const}$.
The corresponding covering
\begin{equation}
\left\{
\begin{array}{lcl}
q_t &=& \lambda \,q_z + u_z \, q_x,
\\
q_y &=& \lambda\, q_s + u_s \, q_x
\end{array}
\right.
\label{lambda_covering}
\end{equation}
was found in \cite{ManakovSantini2006}.
The parameter $\lambda$ in (\ref{lambda_covering})
is non-removable, that is, it cannot be eliminated from (\ref{lambda_covering})
by a gauge transformation (a transformation of the covering that preserves the
covering structure and is identical on the base equation). In accordance with
\cite[\S\S 3.2, 3.6]{KrasilshchikVinogradov1989},
\cite{Krasilshchik2000,IgoninKrasilshchik2002,Marvan2002}, see also
\cite{Cieslinski1993a,Cieslinski1993b}, to prove this claim it suffices to
show that it is impossible to lift the symmetry $V = \phi_{10}-\phi_7 = y\,
\frac{\partial}{\partial y} -z\, \frac{\partial}{\partial z} - u\,
\frac{\partial}{\partial u}$ of Equation (\ref{main}) to a symmetry of
System (\ref{lambda_covering}), while the action of
$\mathrm{exp}\left(\mathrm{ln} (\lambda) \,V\right)$ on
System (\ref{H_covering}) with $H = 1$ gives (\ref{lambda_covering}).

In the same way we can introduce {\it hidden spectral parameters},
\cite{BurtsevZakharovMikhailov}, into (\ref{H_covering}) with $H \not \equiv
\mathrm{const}$.  For example, solution $H = -z/t$ to System (\ref{H_system})
gives the covering (\ref{H_covering}) with non-liftable symmetry
$W_1 =
\phi_9+\alpha\phi_8 +\beta\phi_{11} = (s+\alpha)\, \frac{\partial}{\partial z}
+(y + \beta)\, \frac{\partial}{\partial t}$ for arbitrary $\alpha, \beta \in
\mathbb{R}$. Then the action of $\mathrm{exp}\left(\mathrm{ln} (\lambda)
  \,W_1\right)$ produces the covering (\ref{H_covering}) with $H = -(z+\lambda
\,(s+\alpha))\cdot (t+\lambda\,(y+\beta))^{-1}$.  Similarly, in the case of $H
= -s/y$ we have the non-liftable symmetry $W_2 =\phi_4+ \alpha\phi_6 +
\beta\phi_{12} = (z+\alpha)\, \frac{\partial}{\partial s} +(t + \beta)\,
\frac{\partial}{\partial y}$ and covering (\ref{H_covering}) with $H =
-(s+\lambda \,(z+\alpha))\cdot (y+\lambda\,(t+\beta))^{-1}$.  Combining these
actions, we get the covering of (\ref{main}) defined by the system
\begin{equation}
\left\{
\begin{array}{lcl}
q_t &=&
\displaystyle{
-\frac{\alpha_1 \,z + \alpha_2 \, s +\alpha_3}{\alpha_1 \,t + \alpha_2 \, y +\alpha_4}
\,q_z + u_z \, q_x,
 \phantom{\frac{\frac{1}{1}}{\frac{1}{1}}}
}
\\
q_y &=&
\displaystyle{
-\frac{\alpha_1 \,z + \alpha_2 \, s +\alpha_3}{\alpha_1 \,t + \alpha_2 \, y +\alpha_4}
\, q_s + u_s \, q_x
\phantom{\frac{\frac{1}{1}}{\frac{1}{1}}}
}
\end{array}
\right.
\label{alpha_covering}
\end{equation}
with four non-removable parameters $\alpha_1$, ... , $\alpha_4 \in \mathbb{R}$.


%\vskip 7 pt
Upon excluding $u$ from (\ref{lambda_covering}) we arrive to the equation
\begin{equation}
  \left(\frac{q_y - \lambda \,q_s}{q_x}\right)_z = \left(\frac{q_t - \lambda
      \,q_z}{q_x}\right)_s ,
\label{generalized_5D_MASh_equation}
\end{equation}
or
\begin{equation}
  q_x \, (q_{yz} - q_{ts}) + (q_y - \lambda \, q_s) \, q_{xz} - (q_t-\lambda \,
  q_z) \, q_{xs} = 0,
\label{5D_Veronese_web_equation}
\end{equation}
which can be considered as a 5-dimensional generalization of the so-called ABC
equation
\begin{equation}
  A\, q_x \, q_{ty} +B\, q_y\, q_{tx} + C \, q_t \, q_{xy}=0,
  \qquad A+B+C =0,
\label{ABC_equation}
\end{equation}
which describes three-dimensional Veronese webs
\cite{Zakharevich2000,DunajskiKrynski2013}, see also
\cite{FerapontovKruglikov2012,FerapontovMoss2012}, and of the 4-dimensional
equation
\begin{equation}
  q_y\,q_{xz} + \lambda \, q_x \, q_{ty} - (q_z+\lambda\, q_t)\, q_{xy} = 0
  \label{4D_Veronese_web_eq}
\end{equation}
from \cite{MorozovSergyeyev2014}.

Let us relabel $q \mapsto r$, $\lambda \mapsto \mu$
in (\ref{5D_Veronese_web_equation}) and consider the second copy of
Equation (\ref{5D_Veronese_web_equation}):
%\begin{equation*}$ r_x \, (r_{yz} - r_{ts}) + (r_y - \mu \, r_s) \, r_{xz} - (r_t-\mu \, r_z) \,
  r_{xs} = 0.
$%\end{equation*}
 Then the last equation is related with
(\ref{5D_Veronese_web_equation}) by the B\"acklund transformation
\begin{equation}
  \left\{
    \begin{array}{lcl}
      r_t &=&
      \displaystyle{
        \frac{q_t - \lambda \, q_z}{q_x}\,r_x + \mu \, r_z,
        \phantom{\frac{\frac{1}{1}}{\frac{1}{1}}}
      }
      \\
      r_y &=&
      \displaystyle{
        \frac{q_y - \lambda \, q_s}{q_x} \, r_x + \mu \, r_s,
        \phantom{\frac{\frac{1}{1}}{\frac{1}{1}}}
      }
    \end{array}
  \right.
  \label{BT_for_5D_MASh_equation}
\end{equation}
which is a generalization of the corresponding B\"acklund transformations
for (\ref{ABC_equation}) and (\ref{4D_Veronese_web_eq}) from
\cite{Zakharevich2000} and \cite{MorozovSergyeyev2014}, respectively. Unlike
those transformations, the case of $\mu = \lambda$ is not excluded
in (\ref{BT_for_5D_MASh_equation}). In this case we obtain the B\"acklund
auto-transformation for Equation (\ref{5D_Veronese_web_equation}).

\vskip 7 pt
\noindent{\bf Remark 1}. In the case of $\lambda = 0$
Equation (\ref{generalized_5D_MASh_equation}) coincides with Equation~(16)
from~\cite{MartinezAlonsoShabat}.


Consider now reductions of Equation (\ref{main}) to four- and three dimensional
Lax-integrable equations.

\subsection{First reduction}
We put $s=x$ and then rename $y=z$, $z=y$. This reduces Equation (\ref{main})
to the four-dimensional Equation (\ref{4D_Pavlov_equation}). The corresponding
reduction of (\ref{lambda_covering}) provides a covering with non-removable
parameter for (\ref{4D_Pavlov_equation}) defined by the system
\begin{equation}
\left\{
\begin{array}{lcl}
q_t &=& \lambda \,q_y + u_y \, q_x,
\\
q_z &=& (u_x+\lambda)\, q_x.
\end{array}
\right.
\label{lambda_covering_of_4D_Pavlov_equation}
\end{equation}
In its turn, Equation (\ref{4D_Pavlov_equation}) admits two reductions to
three-dimensional Lax-integrable equations.  When $z=y$,
Equation (\ref{4D_Pavlov_equation}) reduces to equation
\begin{equation}
  u_{yy} = u_{tx} + u_x \, u_{xy} - u_y \, u_{xx}
\label{3D_Pavlov_equation}
\end{equation}(see~\cite{Pavlov2003,Dunajski2004}), while (\ref{lambda_covering}) transforms
to its covering
\begin{equation}
  \left\{
    \begin{array}{lcl}
      q_t &=& (\lambda^2 + \lambda\, u_x + u_y)\,q_x,
      \\
      q_y &=& (u_x+\lambda)\, q_x
    \end{array}
  \right.
  \label{lambda_covering_of_4D_Pavlov_equation}
\end{equation}
found in \cite{Pavlov2003,Dunajski2004}.

Otherwise, if we assume $u$ and $q$ in (\ref{main}) and (\ref{lambda_covering})
to be independent of $t$, so $u_t = 0$, $q_t=0$, and then rename $z=-t$, we
obtain the equation
(see~\cite{Blaszak2002,Pavlov2006,Ovsienko2010,Morozov2009}),
\begin{equation}
  u_{ty} = u_y \, u_{xx}-u_x \, u_{xy}
  \label{rdDym_equation}
\end{equation}
and its covering, \cite{Pavlov2006,Morozov2009},
\begin{equation}
  \left\{
    \begin{array}{lcl}
      q_t &=& -(u_x + \lambda)\,q_x,
      \\
      q_y &=& - \lambda^{-1}\,u_y\, q_x.
    \end{array}
  \right.
  \label{lambda_covering_of_rdDym_equation}
\end{equation}\subsection{Second reduction}
If we put $s=y$ in (\ref{main}) and (\ref{lambda_covering}), then change the
