\label{sec:recursion-operator}
A recursion operator for symmetries of Equation (\ref{main})  was found in \cite{MarvanSergyeyev2012}.
As it was indicated in Section~\ref{sec:symmetries}, local symmetries of (\ref{main})
are solutions to Equation (\ref{eq:1}):
\begin{equation}%\fl
  D_{yz} (\varphi)  = D_{ts}(\varphi)
  + u_s \, D_{xz}(\varphi) + u_{xz} \, D_s(\varphi)  - u_z \, D_{xs}(\varphi) -
  u_{xs} \, D_z(\varphi),
  \label{linearized}
\end{equation}
such that $\varphi$ is a function of $t$, $x$, $y$, $z$, $s$, $u$ and
derivatives of $u$ up to some order, see
\cite{Vinogradov1984,KrasilshchikLychaginVinogradov1986,Bocharov1999} for
detail. In accordance with
\cite{KrasilshchikKersten1994,KrasilshchikKersten1995}, see also
\cite{Marvan1995,MarvanSergyeyev2012} and references therein, the recursion
operator is a B\"acklund auto-transformation for
system (\ref{main}), (\ref{linearized}).
Here we introduce another method to construct recursion operators.
We use the following technique based on ideas of \cite{Sergyeyev2015}, see also
\cite{MalykhNutkuSheftel2004,MarvanSergyeyev2012,MorozovSergyeyev2014}. We
consider {\it shadows of nonlocal symmetries}(or merely shadows, for short)
of Equation (\ref{main}) in the covering (\ref{lambda_covering}). Informally
speaking, the shadows are solutions to (\ref{linearized}) such that $\varphi$
is a function of $t$,\dots,$s$, $u$, $q$ and their derivatives up to some
order, see
\cite{KrasilshchikVinogradov1984,KrasilshchikLychaginVinogradov1986,KrasilshchikVinogradov1989,Bocharov1999}
for detail. For simplicity of calculations we rewrite (\ref{lambda_covering})
in the form
\begin{equation}\label{eq:3}
  \left\{
    \begin{array}{lcl}
      q_z &=& \lambda^{-1} \, (q_t -u_z \, q_x),
      \\
      q_s &=& \lambda^{-1} \, (q_y - u_s \, q_x).
    \end{array}
  \right.
  %\label{inversed_lambda_covering}
\end{equation}
Direct computations held in the {\sc jets} software, \cite{Marvan2009,Jets},
give the following result: every shadow of (\ref{main}) in the
covering (\ref{eq:3}) that depend on derivatives of $u$ and
$q$ up to first order is the sum of a local symmetry and the function
\begin{equation}
  r = (c_1 \, q_t +c_2 \,q_y + Q)\, q_x^{-1},
  \label{shadow}
\end{equation}
where $c_1, c_2 \in \mathbb{R}$ and $Q=Q(t,y,z,s,q)$ is a solution to the
system
\begin{equation}
  Q_y = \lambda \, Q_s, \qquad Q_t = \lambda\, Q_z.
  \label{Q_system}
\end{equation}
We observe, first, that the function (\ref{shadow}) is a solution to the system
\begin{equation}
  \left\{
    \begin{array}{lcl}
      D_z(r) &=& \lambda^{-1} \, (D_t(r) -u_z \, D_x(r)+u_{xz}\,r - c_1 \,u_{tz} -
      c_2\,u_{yz}),
      \\
      D_s(r) &=& \lambda^{-1} \, (D_y(r) - u_s \, D_x(r)+u_{xs}\,r - c_1 \,u_{ts} -
      c_2 \, u_{ys}),
    \end{array}
  \right.
  \label{r_covering}
\end{equation}
and, second, shadows of first order for (\ref{main}) in the
covering (\ref{r_covering}) up to adding a local symmetry are either of the
form $r$(when $c_1^2+c_2^2 \neq 0$), or of the form $R\cdot r$(when $c_1=
c_2 = 0$); here $R=R(t,y,z,s)$ is a solution to System (\ref{Q_system}). In
both cases, we conclude that solutions to (\ref{r_covering}) are solutions
to (\ref{linearized}) as well.

Now suppose that a formal power series
\begin{equation}
  r = \sum \limits_{n=-\infty}^{+\infty} \lambda^n \, r_n
  \label{r_series}
\end{equation}
is a solution to (\ref{r_covering}). Then $r$ is a solution
to (\ref{linearized}), and, since (\ref{linearized}) is independent of
$\lambda$, each $r_n$ is also a solution to (\ref{linearized}). Substituting
the expansion (\ref{r_series}) to (\ref{r_covering}) yields the infinite number
of systems
\begin{equation}
  \left\{
    \begin{array}{lcl}
      D_z(r_n) &=& D_t(r_{n+1}) -u_z \, D_x(r_{n+1})+u_{xz}\,r_{n+1} - c_1 \,u_{tz}
      - c_2\,u_{yz},
      \\
      D_s(r_n) &=& D_y(r_{n+1}) - u_s \, D_x(r_{n+1})+u_{xs}\,r_{n+1} - c_1 \,u_{ts}
      - c_2 \, u_{ys}.
    \end{array}
  \right.
  \label{r_n_covering}
\end{equation}
Now for a fixed $n \in \mathbb{Z}$ in the corresponding
system (\ref{r_n_covering}) we rename $r_n= \bar{\phi}$, $r_{n+1} = \varphi+
c_1 \, u_z + c_2 \, u_s$ and obtain
\begin{equation}
  \left\{
    \begin{array}{lcl}
      D_z(\bar{\phi}) &=& D_t(\varphi) - u_z \, D_x(\varphi)+u_{xz}\, \varphi,
      \\
      D_s(\bar{\phi}) &=& D_y(\varphi) - u_s \, D_x(\varphi)+u_{xs}\, \varphi.
    \end{array}
  \right.
  \label{recursion_operator}
\end{equation}
Since $r_n$, $r_{n+1}$, $u_z$ and $u_s$ are solutions to (\ref{linearized}),
$\varphi$ and $\bar{\phi}$ are also its solutions. Direct computations show
that by virtue of (\ref{main}) System (\ref{recursion_operator}) is compatible
whenever $\varphi$ is a solution to (\ref{linearized}). Expressing
$D_t(\varphi)$ and $D_y(\varphi)$ from (\ref{recursion_operator}) gives
\begin{equation}
  \left\{
    \begin{array}{lcl}
      D_t(\varphi) &=& D_z(\bar{\phi}) + u_z \, D_x(\varphi) - u_{xz}\, \varphi,
      \\
      D_y(\varphi) &=& D_s(\bar{\phi}) + u_s \, D_x(\varphi) - u_{xs}\, \varphi.
    \end{array}
  \right.
  \label{inverse_recursion_operator}
\end{equation}
This system is compatible by virtue of (\ref{main}) whenever $\bar{\phi}$ is a
solution to (\ref{linearized}).  Thus (\ref{recursion_operator})
and (\ref{inverse_recursion_operator}) define B\"acklund auto-transformations
for (\ref{linearized}). In other words, (\ref{recursion_operator})
and (\ref{inverse_recursion_operator}) define a recursion operator $\bar{\phi}
= \EuScript{R}(\varphi)$ and the inverse recursion operator $\varphi =
\EuScript{R}^{-1}(\bar{\phi})$, respectively.

